{#
  Hanko atom.

  Renders the brand mark by inlining an SVG fetched from Sanity. The wrapper
  span carries a `hanko-mount` class that pairs with styles/components/hanko.css;
  that stylesheet pins `display`, sizing, and `fill` on the inner <svg>/<path>
  elements with plain CSS.

  Why plain CSS instead of Tailwind utilities on the SVG itself: Tailwind's
  content scanner only sees source templates, not markup fetched at runtime
  from Sanity. Any utility classes baked into the inlined SVG (e.g.
  `fill-current`) are only generated by accident, so we can't rely on them.
  Safari in particular would leave the paths at the SVG default fill (black)
  on a black background — invisible — even when Chrome happened to render
  correctly. Keeping the runtime-styled rules in hanko.css avoids that whole
  class of cascade/layer surprises.

  Params:
    svg      — inlined SVG markup (from `inlineSvgFromUrl`).
    classes  — utility classes applied to the wrapper span. Use these to set
               color (e.g. `text-secondary-700`) and any caller-specific
               sizing/spacing. The span also fills its parent by default
               (`block w-full h-full`), so callers that size the parent
               element (e.g. an `<a>` with explicit width/height) don't
               need to repeat the size here.
#}
{% macro render(params = {}) %}
  {% set svg = params.svg %}
  {% set classes = params.classes | default("block w-12 text-secondary-700") %}
  <span aria-hidden="true" class="hanko-mount block w-full h-full {{ classes }}">
    {{ svg | safe }}
  </span>
{% endmacro %}